    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>March. 30. 1851</date>.</p>
			<p><placeName>Louisville</placeName>&#44; <date>Sunday&#44; <sic>25thof</sic> second Adar&#44; 5611</date></p>
			<p>Very honored <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">On <date>Friday</date> morning I received your worthy prayer<lb/> books <sic>andhasten</sic> to notify you of this. I shall try to sell as many as<lb/> possible of them between now and <date>Passover</date>. and to collect for the &#34;Oc&#45;<lb/>cident&#34; during the middle days of <date>Passover</date>. And then send you a check<lb/> for the entire sum because the few dollars that I have at present are<lb/> not worth the trouble. I shall then also notify you what success there<lb/> is in the matter of advertising your Bible as you wished.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">When you send your &#34;Occidents&#34; here&#44; address the<lb/> following new subscribers&#58; <persName>M.Godshaw</persName>&#44; <persName>M.Goldberg</persName>&#44; <persName>H.Stern</persName>&#44; <persName>S.Maas</persName>&#44; <persName>Joseph<lb/> Lieber</persName>. The last two I should not like to state outright as being certain<lb/> subscribers. They simply want to try it for a few months.&#44; and then&#44; if<lb/> the newspaper attracts them they will continue to read it. Above all&#44; I<lb/> must confess to you&#44; much to my regret&#44; that I have taken a great deal<lb/> of trouble to obtain new subscribers&#44; and that the success is comparative&#45;<lb/>ly very slight. One element would gladly read it&#44; but is unable to&#59; an&#45;<lb/>other element is naive enough to admit that they are not pious enough<lb/> and not religious enough&#59; one man has no time&#44; another must pay for<lb/> three local newspapers&#44; etc. Only a small portion realizes that a worthy<lb/> undertaking ought to be supported. Last year you sent me several copies<lb/> of which I distributed some to publishers of local newspapers&#44; and others<lb/> to private individuals. This week I collected these loaned copies and<lb/> now place them at your disposal. It will be better if&#44; in the future&#44;<lb/> you send me only one copy&#44; and thus spare yourself the trouble.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In my next letter I shall be in position to tell<lb/> you the cost of the various advertisements in the newspapers etc.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">When you write to me again please have the kind&#45;<lb/>ness to let me know more exactly what your relations are toward your<lb/> former congregation. I still have not given up the hope that in spite</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>2</p>
			<p>of the intervention of other candidates&#44; you will be re&#45;elected. In my<lb/> next letter I shall&#44; if possible&#44; permit myself to send something<lb/> which may be accepted in the Occident&#44; for I do not know but that in<lb/> the course of time it may be desirable for me to become generally bet&#45;<lb/>ter known than I am at present.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">My wife sends you her best greetings. Accept the<lb/> assurance of my esteem&#44; with which I have the honor to sign.</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)">Your most devoted servant&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">B.H.Gotthelf</persName>.</p>
          
        </body>
